  "prompt": "Can a set be both a subset and a proper subset?",
  "response": "Yes, a set can be both a subset and a proper subset of another set, but there is a distinction between the two terms.\n\n1. **Subset**: A set \\( A \\) is a subset of a set \\( B \\) (denoted \\( A \\subseteq B \\)) if every element of \\( A \\) is also an element of \\( B \\). This includes the possibility that \\( A \\) and \\( B \\) are equal; that is, \\( A \\) can be the same set as \\( B \\).\n\n2. **Proper Subset**: A set \\( A \\) is a proper subset of a set \\( B \\) (denoted \\( A \\subset B \\)) if every element of \\( A \\) is also an element of \\( B \\), and additionally, \\( A \\) is not equal to \\( B \\). This means that set \\( B \\) must have at least one element that is not in set \\( A \\).\n\nFor example, if we have:\n\n- Set \\( A = \\{1, 2\\} \\)\n- Set \\( B = \\{1, 2, 3\\} \\)\n\nIn this case, \\( A \\) is a subset of \\( B \\) because all elements of \\( A \\) are in \\( B\\). Additionally, \\( A \\) is a proper subset of \\( B \\) because \\( A \\) is not equal to \\( B\\) (since \\( B \\) has an additional element 3).\n\nConversely, if \\( A \\) were equal to \\( B \\) (i.e., \\( A = B = \\{1, 2\\} \\)), then \\( A \\) would be a subset of \\( B \\) but would not be a proper subset because they are the same set.\n\nIn summary, a set can be a subset of another set, and it can also be a proper subset, but not at the same time if the sets are equal.",
